## Summary

This is a design proposal for #11888. It doesn't have `helpwanted` label but if it's not internal ticket, i would love to help with it.

## Motivation and goals

The reasoning is that WebSockets is a popular transport for SignalR and teams that are heavily depending on tests might have problems since at the moment we can't mock it. 
In our case we are trying to have custom implementation of SignalR with handshake\messages parsing that works based on the Pipelines so we can mock it with TestServer but it might be painful to support such thing in the future.

## In scope

The main use case is to add a way to override WebSocket that is used in SignalR's `WebSocketsTransport` so it can be mocked by TestServer

## Out of scope

Nothing

## Risks / unknowns

The biggest risk is that interface that is described below would be a public contract that might be not so good.
And unknown what is a better way to apply `ClientWebSocketOptions` since it can't be instantiated manually as constructor\ `WebSocketHandle` are internal

## Detailed design

From my understanding one way of fixing it might be adding factory for websockets to `HttpConnectionOptions` in the same way we have `HttpMessageHandlerFactory` for `HttpClient`
https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/62e157b94276bf6e607546b0a46b283f7a6a9b92/src/SignalR/clients/csharp/Http.Connections.Client/src/HttpConnectionOptions.cs#L48-L52

so then we can inject there and add `TestServer.CreateWebSocketClient()`.

The main complication would be that `WebSocketsTransport` uses `ClientWebSocket` since it overrides `_webSocket.Options` by adding headers\proxy\etc, and it can't be replaced to base `WebSocket` class since it doesn't have needed property. 

Maybe as one way of fixing it, a proxy interface can be made like

```
public interface IWebSocketFactory
{
	ClientWebSocketOptions Options { get; }
	async Task<WebSocket> CreateAndConnect(Uri uri, CancellationToken cancellationToken);
}

public class DefaultWebSocketFactory: IWebSocketFactory
{
    private ClientWebSocket _clientSocket;

    public DefaultWebSocketFactory(ClientWebSocket clientSocket)
    {
        _clientSocket = clientSocket;
    }

    public ClientWebSocketOptions Options => _clientSocket.Options;

    public Task ConnectAsync(Uri uri, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        await _clientSocket.ConnectAsync(uri, cancellationToken);
        return _clientSocket;
    }
}
```

then `HttpConnectionOptions` can be updated to have 
```
        public Func<IWebSocketFactory, IWebSocketFactory>? WebSocketFactory { get; set; }
```

And then `WebSocketsTransport` would create `DefaultWebSocketFactory`, pass it to `Options.WebSocketFactory` and use result. So if developers would want to mock WebSockets for SignalR and TestServer, then something like below can be made

```
public class TestWebSocketFactory: IWebSocketFactory
{
    private WebSocketClient _testSocket;

    public TestWebSocketFactory(WebSocketClient testSocket)
    {
        _testSocket = testSocket;
    }

    public ClientWebSocketOptions Options ....

    public Task ConnectAsync(Uri uri, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
         return await _testSocket.ConnectAsync(uri, cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

The thing that i'm not sure is `Options` since options doesn't have public constructor and `WebSocketHandle.CreateDefaultOptions()` is also internal. If it would have it as public, then it can be instantiated and then when `TestWebSocketFactory` creates a connection, it can use `Action<HttpRequest>? ConfigureRequest` in `WebSocketClient` to override request and add cookies\proxy\certificates\etc based on the Options object. 

i'm not sure that it's a good approach since that interface would be public contract and maybe you have another better idea, but if it's doable by external contributors and you are fine with it, i would love to help with PR.

